    "He was knighted in 1975.": [],
    "<em>Painting in Britain</em> was personally thoroughly revised in 1978.": [],
    "He suffered a heart attack in 1985.": [],
    "His magnificent personal library was largely sold to the Getty Museum library in Malibu.": [],
    "Waterhouse's was the last generation of British art historian to be trained before the great influence of the Warburg Institute in London.": [],
    "His brand of art history was one peppered with judgments of art and artists.": [],
    "He had no interest in iconography or philosophical ideas contemporary with the art about which he wrote.": [],
    "He was more than willing to disagree in print about attributions than other art historians, once describing a Christie's attribution of a Gainsborough as \"rot.\"": [],
    "As a historian of English painting, he deprecated the sporting art genre as \"of absorbing interest to the social historian...[but] no business of the historian of art.\"": [],
    "He considered the English portraitist George Romney the equivalent of a \"society\" photographer.": [],
    "He had little appreciation for prints or drawings as works of art.": [],
    "As a historian, he was most associated with Italian and particularly Roman baroque painting.": [],
    "His relatively brief monographs on Sir Joshua Reynolds and Thomas Gainsborough remain the best examinations of the painting genre.": [],
    "His <em>Painting in Britain, 1530-1790</em>, remains a personal vision on the topic: he ended the volume in 1790 so as not to have to deal with the \"untidy\" artists of Fuseli, Turner and Blake (Kitson).": [
